column66: I watched the 8:00 PM screening of Deadpool & Wolverine in Cinema 1, and I’m pretty disappointed. Right from the start, I felt something was off. Initially, I thought it might be a problem with my 3D glasses or just poor 3D effects in the movie. But it wasn’t until the end that I realized I wasn’t the only one having trouble seeing clearly. I heard multiple people around me commenting on the quality. During the credits, it was obvious that the projector was misaligned—the text was doubled, and the top half of the screen was out of focus. When we reported this to the staff, they said they'd address it tomorrow. From what I’ve read in other reviews, it seems they’ve known about this issue for almost a week. This just reinforces my belief that investing in a high-quality home theater setup is the way to go.

Watched Deadpool in Cinema 1. The movie was unfocused  throughout, any text such as in the credits was doubled and it was very difficult to see any action. I tried complaining to the management about it just so they make sure it's fixed. They did not care and immediately went on the defensive saying that nobody left the movie to complain so it must have been alright. No apologies and after pressing the issue I got a noncommittal "will tell the projector guy tomorrow". Edit: I see there are reviews showing there was the same issue last week. This is a high profile movie and it is absolutely ridiculous it hasn't been fixed considering the cost of the tickets and the fact that this is in their flagship cinema room.

Went to see the new Deadpool movie in 3D.\nAfter paying R240 for tickets and another R220 for popcorn and drinks. (Only for 2 people, that totals to R460) we were told that the 3D glasses are not included in the price and should be bought extra. We then received our much smaller than usual popcorn with the 2 sad spice sachets.\nWe could almost watch the movie without the glasses as it felt like they made the movie extremely blurry and weren'tworking. We really wanted to go see this movie so we bit the bullet and payed the high price but after tonight I can totally see why people don't go to the cinema anymore. After paying R500 for a movie we could hardly see, I wish I could get a refund. Thinking of going to the movies? Don't bother

I went to see Napoleon during December. Sadly, a potentially great movie experience was ruined by very poor projection. The entire movie was rather dark and the visuals under-illuminated. I remember a similar experience a few years back, watching Midway at Menlyn.\nOnce the movie starts, one cannot go out to complain, because then you lose the plot. So you sit there for two hours, irritated by the fact that a movie you had been looking forward to, is now being poorly dished up. And the fact that you had paid for that questionable privilege. For me, that was the last movie house experience. I love movies, but from now on it will be the streaming services at home, on the smaller big screen. I simply cannot fathom how Ster-Kinekor hopes to stay in business if they cannot manage such important details.

R40 per person, anytime and any day and don't need the SK Membership Card to only pay R40. Even 3D is way better priced than other malls and cinemas. Safe basement parking (plus minus R15 depending on time spent). Bathrooms super clean and free on cinema level. Ground floor is paid toilets. A Spur, Fish Aways and Steers as neighbours inside the building and Burger King and KFC on the corner outside, you can't go wrong to make it food, fun, entertainment and lasting memories on a budget.
